; satsang-guidance-event.form - edited transcripts offered as a guidance turn.
;
; A satsang companion listens first. When the circle explicitly offers a turn,
; names the presence, or presses the button, the edited transcript can become a
; guidance request to Sema or another invoked presence. The protocol keeps all
; detected utterances visible, carries edits as edits, and records the target
; presence and turn mode before any transmission is asked for.
;
; Carrier:
;   experiments/satsang-mac-app - SwiftUI Mac desktop app. It tails the local
;   transcript JSONL, listens to the room microphone after explicit Start
;   Listening, lets the holder edit utterances, and writes the request to
;   ~/.coherence-network/satsang-guidance/events.jsonl plus the latest JSON and
;   .form receipt. No external receiver is invoked by the GUI. No-speech
;   intervals restart recognition and the visible mic level shows whether the
;   room is reaching the input device. The mic meter comes alive separately from
;   Speech Recognition authorization so permission delay is visible instead of
;   silent. On Send, the GUI asks the local Form CLI first and records the
;   body/RAG sufficiency receipt in the JSON and .form event; a remote oracle is
;   only requested as an explicit insufficient-local route, not called by the GUI.
;   The Send path also writes a local trusted room-memory receipt under
;   ~/.coherence-network/agent-room-memory and includes prior-session context in
;   the request. Speaker continuity is keyed by transcript voice_id / speaker_id
;   when present, or by visible channel label when not; channel-only continuity
;   is not presented as verified identity.
;   File, process, audio-input, and speech-transcript resources cross one
;   generic host OS resource-door receipt in the Swift core. The receipt carries
;   resolved macOS, Windows, and Android carrier mappings for every resource
;   kind; live state is detected on macOS today, while Windows/Android device
;   packages still promote declared doors to observed/open runtime receipts. The
;   shared logic remains Form-native and rejects Python, Go, Rust, and
;   TypeScript as app-boundary runtimes.
;
; Body:
;   form/form-stdlib/satsang-guidance-event.fk decides whether the event is a
;   valid guidance request or must hold. It accepts Sema, the satsang companion,
;   or a new invoked presence; accepts turn-offered, named-and-asked, and
;   button-invoked modes; requires a non-empty transcript, all detected lines
;   included, and a present question. Proof:
;   form/form-stdlib/tests/satsang-guidance-event-band.fk -> 255.
;   form/form-stdlib/satsang-listen-route.fk keeps the listen/transcribe route
;   remote-last with form-cli-sufficiency.fk. Proof:
;   form/form-stdlib/tests/satsang-listen-route-band.fk -> 255.
;   form/form-stdlib/satsang-host-boundary.fk names the generic host ABI,
;   detected resource doors, resolved platform carriers, and forbidden
;   app-boundary runtimes. Proof:
;   form/form-stdlib/tests/satsang-host-boundary-band.fk -> 131071.
;   form/form-stdlib/satsang-room-memory.fk names explicit local session memory,
;   speaker continuity, no-hidden-capture, and later context. Proof:
;   form/form-stdlib/tests/satsang-room-memory-band.fk -> 255.
;
; Boundary:
;   The event is an offer, not an interruption. The GUI does not decide that a
;   presence should speak on its own. It records that the turn was offered, then
;   gives the transcript and question to the presence lane.
